"""
Fill script: 2 Samuel mkt-christ ch17, 18, 24 — fills missing Christological commentary.
Ch17: Ahithophel's counsel / Hushai's counter-counsel / the betrayer's suicide.
Ch18: Battle of the forest / Absalom's death / David's lament.
Ch24: The census / the plague / Araunah's threshing floor (future temple site / type of atonement).
Existing entries (v14, v23 in ch17; v9, v33 in ch18; v10, v16, v18, v25 in ch24) are not overwritten.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

FILL = {
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Ahithophel&rsquo;s strategic counsel to Absalom — pursue David this very night with twelve thousand men, strike while he is weary and discouraged, scatter the people — is the counsel of a traitor who once served the king he now seeks to destroy. The Christological parallel is precise: Judas Iscariot, once numbered among the Twelve, guided the authorities to arrest Jesus at night (Matt 26:47-50) with specific knowledge of where to find him. Ahithophel is the OT type who makes Judas&rsquo;s role legible: the intimate betrayer who turns strategic expertise against the anointed one. The night-urgency and the knowledge of the king&rsquo;s location and vulnerability are common to both betrayals.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ahithophel&rsquo;s plan targets David alone — <em>ûhikkîtî ʾet hammelek lĕbaḏḏô</em>, &lsquo;I will strike the king only&rsquo; — proposing a surgical strike that would collapse the rebellion and counterinsurgency simultaneously. The typological irony is that the betrayer always imagines that eliminating the king will end the resistance; both Ahithophel and Judas act on the premise that if the anointed one is removed, the movement dies. But both betray a fatal misunderstanding: the death of the king is not the end but the beginning. David will survive ch17; the greater David will be struck and rise on the third day, his death becoming the very foundation of the kingdom that cannot be shaken (Heb 12:28).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Ahithophel&rsquo;s stated goal — bring all the people back to the king as a bride returns to her husband — is a grotesque appropriation of covenant-marriage language in the service of treason. The reunion of the people with Absalom is framed as a wedding homecoming, deploying the <em>kallāh</em> image that elsewhere describes Israel&rsquo;s covenant relationship with YHWH (Jer 2:2; Isa 62:5). Wickedness borrows the vocabulary of covenant loyalty. The antitype is Christ&rsquo;s genuine covenant-wedding: the Son of David brings his people home not through treachery but through the blood of the new covenant (Matt 26:28; Rev 19:7-9), and the reunion is not the restoration of a usurper&rsquo;s rule but the Lamb&rsquo;s marriage feast.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The counsel pleased Absalom and all the elders of Israel — a moment of apparent consensus built entirely on treachery. The ease with which Ahithophel&rsquo;s counsel is received reflects the moral bankruptcy of a court that has already rejected the anointed king. The elders of Israel who endorse the plan to destroy David stand in typological parallel to the chief priests and elders who convened to plan Jesus&rsquo;s destruction (Matt 26:3-4), and their consensus achieves the same theological result: the human assembly aligned against YHWH&rsquo;s anointed (Ps 2:2-3) becomes the instrument of their own undoing, since YHWH will nullify the counsel they have agreed upon (v14).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Absalom calls for Hushai the Archite to hear a second counsel — his decision to seek a confirming voice will prove fatal to his rebellion. The Christological dimension lies in YHWH&rsquo;s providential overruling of human strategic calculation: Absalom&rsquo;s curiosity, which seems like prudent leadership, is the mechanism by which God frustrates the betrayer&rsquo;s plan. Acts 2:23 establishes the NT theology of this pattern: &lsquo;this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men.&rsquo; Divine sovereignty and human agency both operate; Absalom&rsquo;s choice to hear Hushai is both free and foreordained.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Hushai is asked to repeat what Ahithophel said, so that Absalom can evaluate both plans — Absalom presenting himself as a judicious leader consulting his advisors. The irony is sharp: Absalom thinks he is exercising royal discernment; he is actually fulfilling YHWH&rsquo;s decree that Ahithophel&rsquo;s counsel be overthrown (v14). The Christological register here is the hiddenness of divine providence within ordinary political processes — neither Absalom nor his counselors know that the outcome of this deliberation has already been determined. The same hiddenness characterizes the Passion narrative: Pilate, the Sanhedrin, and Judas all act freely, yet fulfill what &lsquo;God&rsquo;s hand and plan had predestined to take place&rsquo; (Acts 4:28).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Hushai opens his counter-counsel by challenging Ahithophel&rsquo;s plan directly — &lsquo;the counsel that Ahithophel has given is not good at this time.&rsquo; <em>Lōʾ ṭôḇāh hāʿēṣāh ʾăšer yāʿaṣ ʾăḥîṯōp̄el bappaʿam hazzōʾt</em>. The explicit rejection of the betrayer&rsquo;s counsel by a loyal servant typifies the pattern of intercession: the one who stands between the anointed king and destruction must refuse the logic of betrayal. In the NT, the Paraclete — the Spirit of truth — counters the accuser&rsquo;s counsel in the heavenly court (John 16:7-11; Rev 12:10-11), and those who stand with Christ refuse the world&rsquo;s &lsquo;counsel&rsquo; that he is not worth following.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Hushai warns Absalom that David and his men are mighty warriors — <em>gibbôrê ḥayil</em>, men of valor — experienced in battle, with the ferocity of a mother bear robbed of her cubs in the open field. The bear-image (<em>dōḇ šakkûl baśśāḏeh</em>) is the OT idiom for lethal maternal aggression (Prov 17:12; Hos 13:8). Christologically, Hushai&rsquo;s warning that David is dangerous resonates with the NT proclamation that the risen Christ is not merely a defeated victim but the Lord of glory who has disarmed principalities and powers (Col 2:15). The enemies of the anointed king consistently underestimate what they are facing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Hushai elaborates: David may already have hidden in a pit or some other place — if some of the people fall at the first assault, word will spread that Absalom&rsquo;s forces suffered a defeat, and even the valiant warrior (<em>gibbôr lēḇ kᵉlēḇ hāʾaryēh</em>, whose heart is like the heart of a lion) will be seized with terror. The argument exploits the fear of rumor — a first setback becomes catastrophic not because of military reality but because of psychological contagion. The typological point is that the forces arrayed against the anointed king are ultimately driven by fear, not conviction, and fear-based coalitions dissolve at the first sign of the king&rsquo;s power. The disciples&rsquo; post-resurrection proclamation of Christ&rsquo;s victory does exactly this — it spreads the &lsquo;rumor&rsquo; of his rising that his enemies cannot suppress (Matt 28:11-15).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Hushai&rsquo;s counsel hinges on the psychological fragility of even the bravest Israelite soldier when confronting David&rsquo;s seasoned warriors: &lsquo;all Israel knows your father is a mighty man, and those who are with him are men of valor.&rsquo; The appeal to what &lsquo;all Israel knows&rsquo; about David uses collective memory to undermine the rebellion&rsquo;s confidence. The Christological resonance is in the unspoken premise: the Son of David is recognized even by his enemies as someone whose power cannot simply be overcome by numbers or strategy. The acknowledgment of the anointed one&rsquo;s superior power by those who oppose him appears throughout the Passion narrative (John 11:47-48: &lsquo;if we let him go on like this, everyone will believe in him&rsquo;).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hushai&rsquo;s counter-proposal: gather all Israel from Dan to Beersheba, a multitude like the sand of the sea, with Absalom leading them personally into battle. The geography of the proposal — the full Abrahamic extent of Israel — invokes the covenant promise given to Abraham (Gen 22:17, sand of the sea) in the service of rebellion. Absalom&rsquo;s rebellion thus simultaneously parodies and desecrates the covenant: the Abrahamic multitude is mustered not to bless all nations but to destroy the chosen king. This inversion anticipates the armies of Rev 20:8, where the nations gathered &lsquo;as numerous as the sand of the sea&rsquo; are assembled against the holy city — the final parody of Abrahamic blessing turned into eschatological assault.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Hushai&rsquo;s proposed assault — falling on David wherever he is found, like the dew falling on the ground — uses the dew image (<em>hannāšal ʿālāyw kaʾăšer yippōl haṭṭal ʿal hāʾăḏāmāh</em>) as an image of overwhelming and inescapable saturation. The dew-image in the OT more commonly describes blessing and provision (Deut 32:2; Ps 133:3; Mic 5:7) — here Hushai deliberately perverts it to describe annihilation. The typological irony: what Absalom plans as David&rsquo;s overwhelming destruction is precisely what YHWH plans as his people&rsquo;s renewal. The dew of blessing that Hushai co-opts for a counsel of betrayal reappears in its original register in the resurrection morning — the abundance of new life that falls on those who trust the risen king.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The final element of Hushai&rsquo;s counsel — if David escapes into a city, pull it into the river stone by stone so that not a pebble remains — is rhetorically maximal: total destruction, no remnant. The counsel&rsquo;s extremism is deliberate on Hushai&rsquo;s part; he is not offering practical military advice but spinning out an ambitious scenario to appeal to Absalom&rsquo;s vanity. The phrase &lsquo;not even a pebble&rsquo; (<em>ʿad ʾăšer lōʾ yimmāṣēʾ šām gam ṣᵉrôr ʾeḥāḏ</em>) echoes the hyperbolic completeness-language of covenant threats (Deut 28:62); Hushai turns the rhetoric of covenant judgment into a flattering promise. The greater David, by contrast, loses not one of those the Father has given him (John 6:39) — the zero-loss guarantee that stands against every counsel of annihilation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Hushai immediately informs the priests Zadok and Abiathar of both counsels — he has discharged his intelligence function as David&rsquo;s agent. The messenger chain — Hushai to the priests to their sons to David — is the providential communication network that will preserve the king. The Christological pattern here is the faithful remnant who preserves the line of the anointed even under hostile conditions: in the NT this is the small group of women and disciples who remain at the cross and empty tomb while the broader community has fled or betrayed. The preservation of the king&rsquo;s life depends on faithful transmission of crucial information across a hostile environment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Hushai&rsquo;s urgent message to David — do not lodge at the fords of the wilderness, but cross over immediately — reflects the gravity of the moment: even with Ahithophel&rsquo;s counsel overthrown, delay could prove fatal. The urgency of the warning to cross the Jordan is typologically resonant with every OT exodus and flight: the Jordan crossing is the boundary between death and life, danger and safety. In the NT the urgency of response to the gospel carries similar temporal weight — &lsquo;Now is the acceptable time; now is the day of salvation&rsquo; (2 Cor 6:2). Delay in spiritual matters is as dangerous as Hushai warned delay would be for David on the banks of the Jordan.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jonathan and Ahimaaz are stationed at En-rogel — the spring just outside Jerusalem — so they can relay messages without entering the city. A servant girl serves as intermediary, carrying information between the priestly network and the two young men who will run to David. The covert communication web required to preserve David&rsquo;s life — multiple intermediaries, concealment, risk — typifies the hiddenness in which the kingdom of God operates under hostility. The kingdom advances through unlikely intermediaries: a servant girl, anonymous young men. In the NT the gospel&rsquo;s first witnesses are women whose testimony was dismissed by official standards (Luke 24:11), yet they carry the message that changes the world.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jonathan and Ahimaaz are spotted going and they hide in a well at Bahurim — a servant woman spreads grain over the well&rsquo;s mouth so the covering appears undisturbed. The concealment in the well (<em>wayyērēḏû bᵉʾēr bᵉḇêt ʾîš bĕḇaḥûrîm</em>) recalls Joseph in the cistern (Gen 37:24), Jeremiah in the pit (Jer 38:6), and anticipates the sealed tomb that cannot hold the one it is meant to conceal. Every attempt to suppress the transmission of the royal message — pit, tomb, stone — fails because YHWH preserves the witnesses he appoints. The woman&rsquo;s grain-covering is a small act of covenant loyalty that participates in the preservation of the Davidic line.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The woman&rsquo;s quick thinking — spreading the grain over the well&rsquo;s mouth — makes the hiding place invisible to Absalom&rsquo;s servants, who pass through Bahurim without finding the two messengers. The grain spread over the well is a domestic concealment that saves the kingdom; the humble substance of everyday life (grain, a millstone in Judg 9:53) repeatedly appears in the OT as the instrument that diverts or defeats the powerful. The pattern culminates in the cross — the &lsquo;stumbling block and foolishness&rsquo; of 1 Cor 1:23, the apparent defeat that becomes the decisive victory. YHWH&rsquo;s instruments of preservation are consistently hidden beneath mundane appearances.</p>",
    "20": "<p>When Absalom&rsquo;s men search for the runners and cannot find them, they return to Jerusalem empty-handed — the intelligence mission has failed. The failed search typifies the recurring pattern of hostile forces looking for the anointed one or his witnesses and finding nothing: the soldiers guarding the tomb who must report that the stone was moved and the body is gone (Matt 28:11-15), the authorities who cannot silence the apostles despite repeated arrest (Acts 5:17-42). The failure of the search at Bahurim and the failure of the guard at the tomb are structurally the same: YHWH renders the hostile search fruitless, and the message gets through.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Jonathan and Ahimaaz come up out of the well and go to tell King David — the message travels from concealment to transmission. The emergence from the well is a minor resurrection image in the typological pattern: those who were hidden as if dead rise to deliver the life-saving message. The direct speech to David — <em>qûmû ʿiḇrû ʾet hammayim</em>, &lsquo;arise, cross the water&rsquo; — is the command of salvation. The imperative <em>qûmû</em>, &lsquo;arise,&rsquo; carries the same verb as the resurrection proclamation: what is said to David in flight anticipates the angel&rsquo;s word that David&rsquo;s greater Son has arisen.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David and all the people with him cross the Jordan before dawn — the entire household makes the passage in safety. The Jordan crossing at night, under the threat of Absalom&rsquo;s army, echoes Israel&rsquo;s crossing of the Red Sea and the later Joshua-crossing at the end of the wilderness wandering. Each of these Jordan/Red Sea crossings is an exodus moment — passage from death to life, from captivity to freedom. David&rsquo;s nighttime flight across the Jordan typologically encodes the same theology: the anointed king leads his people through the waters that would otherwise overwhelm them. The greater crossing is Christ&rsquo;s own baptism and death (Luke 12:50) through which he leads his people from death to life.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Shimei son of Gera from the house of Saul had cursed David during the flight (16:5-13); now Ahithophel&rsquo;s home city of Giloh and the house of Machir shelter David&rsquo;s loyalists. The support network — Shobi, Machir, Barzillai — represents those who remain faithful to the exiled king when the political tide has turned against him. The pattern of loyal provision for the king in his hour of exile and vulnerability is a type of the provision for Christ in his earthly ministry (Luke 8:2-3, the women who provided for Jesus out of their means) and the post-resurrection provision for the early church (Acts 2:44-45; 4:34-35). Faithfulness to the anointed king in his hour of weakness is covenant loyalty in its most costly form.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Amasa, Absalom&rsquo;s general, is the son of a man named Ithra the Israelite, who married Abigail daughter of Nahash, sister of Zeruiah. The genealogical note on the rebellion&rsquo;s military commander establishes that Amasa is David&rsquo;s nephew — he is family. The rebellion against David is thus a family war, not merely a political one. The betrayal from within the covenant household — those who should be closest to the king using their proximity for destruction — is the deepest type of the NT&rsquo;s portrait of Judas: &lsquo;even my close friend in whom I trusted, who ate my bread, has lifted his heel against me&rsquo; (Ps 41:9; John 13:18). The covenant bond violated from within is the sharpest instrument of the anointed one&rsquo;s suffering.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Absalom encamps in Gilead, the Transjordan territory — the rebellion has spread to the east bank as well as Jerusalem. The occupation of Gilead by the rebel army establishes the geographic scope of the crisis: the entire nation is effectively at war against its anointed king. The scattering of the kingdom typifies the NT&rsquo;s description of what happens when the Shepherd is struck — &lsquo;I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered&rsquo; (Matt 26:31; Zech 13:7). David&rsquo;s kingdom appears to have dissolved; so did the nascent kingdom of Christ at the cross. Both moments of apparent dissolution precede the decisive restoration of the king&rsquo;s authority.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Shobi son of Nahash from Rabbah of the Ammonites, Machir son of Ammiel from Lo-debar (the same Lo-debar where Mephibosheth had lived, ch9), and Barzillai the Gileadite from Rogelim — three loyal men from outside David&rsquo;s own tribe supply him in exile. Shobi is an Ammonite; Machir had sheltered Mephibosheth and aligned with David&rsquo;s covenant-kindness; Barzillai is a wealthy Gileadite. The diversity of David&rsquo;s supporters in exile — including a Gentile — typifies the breadth of Christ&rsquo;s support base during his earthly ministry and the post-Pentecost mission: the Gentiles, the marginalized, and those who have received covenant-kindness become the core of the faithful remnant.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The supplies brought to David — beds, basins, earthen vessels, wheat, barley, flour, parched grain, beans, lentils, honey, curds, sheep, and cheese — are the material substance of exile survival: complete provision in a time of flight. The abundance of the list signals that YHWH&rsquo;s covenant provision does not fail even in the wilderness of exile. The parallel with the provision for Elijah by the ravens (1 Kings 17:4-6) and the angel (1 Kings 19:5-7) and the wilderness manna is explicit: the anointed one who is driven into exile is sustained by supernatural provision through human instruments. In the NT, the angels who ministered to Jesus in the wilderness (Matt 4:11) and the women who provided for his ministry are the antitype of Shobi, Machir, and Barzillai.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The provision is given &lsquo;because they said, the people are hungry and weary and thirsty in the wilderness&rsquo; — the motivation is pastoral compassion for the condition of David&rsquo;s following, not merely loyalty to the king. The three adjectives — hungry, weary, thirsty — are the three conditions of the wilderness that YHWH had addressed through Moses (manna, water, rest), and they are the three conditions that Christ addresses in his ministry: he feeds the hungry (Matt 14:13-21), gives rest to the weary (Matt 11:28), and gives water to the thirsty (John 4:14; 7:37-38). The wilderness provision for David&rsquo;s people is a type of the Messianic provision for all who follow the Son of David through their own wilderness.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>David musters his forces at Mahanaim — the same place whose name (&lsquo;two camps&rsquo;) had received its name from Jacob&rsquo;s encounter with the angels of God (Gen 32:2). The numbering of commanders and troops at Mahanaim activates this geographic theology: the anointed king preparing for battle at the site of angelic encounter suggests divine reinforcement is present, even when invisible. The pattern of the human army reinforced by unseen divine forces runs through the OT (2 Kings 6:17, Elisha&rsquo;s chariots of fire) and culminates in Rev 19:11-14 where the armies of heaven accompany the Son of David at his final battle. David&rsquo;s organization of his forces is the human side of a battle YHWH has already determined to win.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David divides the army into three parts under Joab, Abishai, and Ittai the Gittite — the same threefold division that Gideon used against Midian (Judg 7:16) and that Saul used at Jabesh-gilead (1 Sam 11:11). The structural repetition of the three-division pattern across Israel&rsquo;s holy wars typifies the covenant warfare in which YHWH multiplies force through division — a paradox of military wisdom (dividing a smaller force against a larger) that is redeemed by divine empowerment. Ittai the Gittite, a Gentile who pledged loyalty to David in 15:21 using Ruth-language, now commands a third of the king&rsquo;s army — the Gentile who chose the covenant people is entrusted with the covenant people&rsquo;s defense.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The people urge David not to go into battle himself: &lsquo;you are worth ten thousand of us.&rsquo; The <em>ʿattāh ṭôḇ lānû meʿăśārāh ălāpîm</em> (you are better to us than ten thousand) values the king&rsquo;s survival above the combined survival of the army. This royal arithmetic has a Christological dimension: the one anointed king is irreplaceable in a way the many warriors are not. The NT equivalent is the doctrine of the irreplaceable mediator: &lsquo;there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus&rsquo; (1 Tim 2:5). The death of the king ends the kingdom; the death of Christ opens it. The irony is that the greater David must go into the battle his people cannot fight — must go precisely where they tell him not to go.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The king stands by the city gate while the army marches out — the image of the enthroned king at the gate watching his people go to war on his behalf. The gate is the seat of judicial authority in Israelite culture (Ruth 4:1; Prov 31:23), so David at the gate is simultaneously watching and presiding. The Christological reversal: David remains at the gate and sends his army; Christ goes ahead of his people into the ultimate battle with death (Heb 2:14-15), dying the death they cannot die for themselves and emerging victorious. The anointed who watches is the lesser type; the anointed who descends is the fulfillment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David charges Joab, Abishai, and Ittai: &lsquo;deal gently with the young man Absalom for my sake.&rsquo; The verb <em>lāʾaṭ</em> means to handle carefully, gently, with restraint — the king&rsquo;s mercy toward his rebellious son that his commanders will refuse (vv12-14). The command encodes the theology of divine longsuffering: YHWH commands that his anointed ones and prophets not be harmed (Ps 105:15), and Christ in his passion does not call down the twelve legions of angels (Matt 26:53). The father-king who desires mercy rather than destruction for the rebellious son anticipates the father in Luke 15:20 who runs toward the returning prodigal. David&rsquo;s mercy toward Absalom is the human image of what the Father desires for the rebellious children of Adam.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The battle takes place in the forest of Ephraim — a wooded highland terrain in Transjordan that will prove decisive in ways Absalom cannot anticipate. The choice of battlefield is the narrator&rsquo;s setup for the theological climax: the forest, not the sword, will consume the greater part of Absalom&rsquo;s forces. The engagement in the forest echoes the OT motif of YHWH fighting through nature rather than merely through armies (Josh 10:11, the hailstones; Judg 5:20-21, the stars fought against Sisera). Divine warfare uses creation itself; the created order cooperates with the covenant king against those who rebel against YHWH&rsquo;s anointed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The defeat of Israel before David&rsquo;s servants is total — twenty thousand men fall that day. The scale of the defeat (twenty thousand) signals that this is not merely a military engagement but a providential judgment: YHWH&rsquo;s covenant curse on those who rebel against his anointed (Ps 2:1-6; 2 Sam 7:14). The narrator uses the same vocabulary as descriptions of YHWH&rsquo;s defeat of Israel&rsquo;s enemies — the enemies of the covenant king are defeated as YHWH&rsquo;s enemies are defeated. The eschatological amplification is Armageddon (Rev 19:17-21): the complete defeat of all who array themselves against the Son of David, with no victory in sight for the assembled armies of rebellion.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The forest devours more men than the sword — <em>wayyereḇ hayaʿar leʾĕkōl bāʿām mēʾăšer ʾāḵlāh haḥereḇ</em>. The forest&rsquo;s consumption exceeds the sword&rsquo;s. The image activates the OT theology of creation as the arm of YHWH&rsquo;s judgment: the floods (Gen 7), the sea (Exod 14), the Jordan (Josh 3), the fire from heaven (1 Kings 18:38) are all creation acting as covenant enforcer. The forest of Ephraim consuming Absalom&rsquo;s troops is YHWH&rsquo;s created order defending the anointed king. In the same way the creation that groans under the curse (Rom 8:20-22) will be renewed when the Son of David brings his enemies to nothing: what creation does instrumentally in judgment anticipates the eschatological renewal of all things.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A certain man sees Absalom hanging in the terebinth and reports to Joab — the witness who observes the king&rsquo;s enemy caught by the tree but refuses to act against David&rsquo;s explicit order (v5). The witness who sees and reports rather than acts is bound by the royal command: the soldier knows David desires Absalom alive. This restraint in the face of an obvious target is a type of the NT ethic of leaving judgment to God rather than taking it into human hands (Rom 12:19). The man who refuses to kill Absalom represents those who will not act against the enemy of the anointed when the king has not authorized it — a virtue that Joab will refuse to imitate.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Joab rebukes the soldier for not striking Absalom — &lsquo;I would have given you ten pieces of silver and a belt.&rsquo; The offer of reward for extrajudicial killing directly contradicts David&rsquo;s order. Joab&rsquo;s military pragmatism overrides covenant loyalty to the king&rsquo;s command: for Joab, Absalom is a strategic problem to be solved, not a son for whom the father has expressed specific mercy. The tension between pragmatic ruthlessness and covenantal mercy is not a peripheral theme — it is the axis of ch18. Christ&rsquo;s passion is the place where this tension reaches its resolution: the Father&rsquo;s mercy toward the rebellious is accomplished not by overlooking the offense but by the anointed Son absorbing the judgment the rebels deserve.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The soldier&rsquo;s refusal is grounded in David&rsquo;s public order — &lsquo;the king charged you and Abishai and Ittai in my hearing, saying, beware that none touch the young man Absalom.&rsquo; The explicit covenantal basis of the refusal — the king&rsquo;s spoken command is publicly binding — models the type of obedience that the NT requires of those who would serve the greater King. Jesus&rsquo;s commands are not guidelines to be bypassed when pragmatic outcomes seem to justify it; they are the authoritative word of the anointed king whose word stands (Matt 5:18; 24:35). The soldier&rsquo;s literalism about the king&rsquo;s command is, ironically, more theologically faithful than Joab&rsquo;s pragmatism.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The soldier adds a prudential argument: if he had killed Absalom, he would have acted against himself — because nothing is hidden from the king (<em>kî ʾên dāḇār nistār min hammelek</em>). The phrase &lsquo;nothing is hidden from the king&rsquo; is an assertion about the omniscience of royal authority that the theology of divine kingship amplifies to its maximum: YHWH sees everything that is done under heaven (Ps 139:1-12; Job 34:21-22). The soldier&rsquo;s fear of the king&rsquo;s hidden knowledge is a type of the NT&rsquo;s exhortation to live coram Deo — before the face of God — knowing that every act is transparent to the one before whom all must give account (Heb 4:13; 2 Cor 5:10).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Joab refuses the soldier&rsquo;s argument and takes three spears in his hand to thrust through Absalom&rsquo;s heart while Absalom still lives. Joab acts against the king&rsquo;s explicit mercy-command because he judges Absalom&rsquo;s continued existence a political liability. The three spears through the heart of the king&rsquo;s rebellious son have no type in Christ&rsquo;s passion — rather they typify the human unwillingness to exercise the mercy that the divine king commands. Where David desired Absalom alive, YHWH desires all to come to repentance (2 Pet 3:9); human agents of judgment (like Joab) consistently impose a harsher standard than the king requires. The soldier who obeyed the spirit of mercy and the commander who violated it represent two responses to the covenant king&rsquo;s call to longsuffering.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ten of Joab&rsquo;s armor-bearers surround Absalom and kill him — corporate action ensuring the prince is dead, no possibility of revival. The ten young men executing what Joab began is the final completion of the act that violated David&rsquo;s command. The contrast with the ten lepers (Luke 17:12-19) or the ten virgins (Matt 25:1-13) — where the number ten represents completeness and accountability — sharpens the theological point: the complete execution of judgment against the king&rsquo;s rebellious son is simultaneously the act most contrary to the king&rsquo;s expressed will. When human judgment acts against the mercy of the anointed king, it does so with decisive thoroughness.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Joab blows the horn and the people return from pursuing Israel — the battle is over, there is no need for further killing. The horn-blast ending the pursuit typifies the eschatological mercy within judgment: YHWH&rsquo;s judgments have an endpoint, a moment when the destruction stops. The Nineveh narrative (Jonah 4:2) and the New Exodus vision of the restoration of Israel both rest on this same divine attribute — YHWH&rsquo;s reluctance to consume entirely, the remnant preserved within the judgment. The horn that ends the battle is the type of the last trumpet (1 Cor 15:52; 1 Thess 4:16) that ends the era of judgment and inaugurates the era of resurrection and restoration.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Absalom is thrown into a large pit in the forest and covered with a great heap of stones — the customary burial of a cursed enemy in Israel (Josh 7:25-26, Achan; Josh 8:29, the king of Ai; Josh 10:27, the five kings). The stone-heap burial marks Absalom as under covenant curse — the king&rsquo;s rebellious son receives the burial of Israel&rsquo;s enemies. The typological contrast with Christ&rsquo;s burial is stark: Christ is buried honorably in a borrowed tomb by a prominent man (Joseph of Arimathea, John 19:38-42), fulfilling Isa 53:9 (&lsquo;they made his grave with the rich&rsquo;), while Absalom the rebel receives the burial of the accursed. The manner of burial in both cases signals the theological verdict on the one buried.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The narrator notes that Absalom had erected a monument for himself in the King&rsquo;s Valley during his lifetime because he had no son to keep his name in remembrance — he had named the pillar after himself, &lsquo;Absalom&rsquo;s Monument.&rsquo; The monument built during life for posthumous name-preservation (<em>lᵉhazᵉkîr šᵉmô</em>) is an act of self-glorification in the exact spirit of Babel (Gen 11:4: &lsquo;let us make a name for ourselves&rsquo;). Absalom&rsquo;s monument is the anti-type of the covenant: the covenant people&rsquo;s name is preserved not by self-erection but by divine promise (Gen 12:2; 2 Sam 7:9). Christ, who &lsquo;made himself nothing&rsquo; (Phil 2:7), receives the name above every name not from his own monument but from the Father (Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Ahimaaz son of Zadok asks Joab&rsquo;s permission to run with the news to the king — &lsquo;let me run and carry news to the king that YHWH has delivered him from the hand of his enemies.&rsquo; The framing of the battle&rsquo;s outcome as YHWH&rsquo;s deliverance of the king (<em>šᵉpāṭô YHWH miyyaḏ ʾōyᵉḇāyw</em>) is theologically significant: Ahimaaz attributes the victory not to military skill but to divine vindication of the anointed. This is the theology of holy war: the king&rsquo;s victories are YHWH&rsquo;s victories. The NT proclamation of Christ&rsquo;s resurrection uses the same grammar — &lsquo;God raised him up&rsquo; (Acts 2:24), the divine vindication of the anointed one over the enemies that killed him.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Joab denies Ahimaaz permission, telling him to carry news another day — &lsquo;today you shall carry no news, for the king&rsquo;s son is dead.&rsquo; Joab&rsquo;s sensitivity about the message and its bearer reflects his awareness that the victory is shadowed by a grief that will overwhelm the king. The complexity of the message — military victory alongside personal loss — is a type of the gospel&rsquo;s own complexity: the resurrection announcement is simultaneously the news of death and of life, of grief transformed into joy. The messenger who must carry both the victory and the death of the beloved is not unlike those who first proclaimed Christ&rsquo;s resurrection, which required recounting his death before announcing his rising.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Cushite is sent instead — a foreigner who runs to David with the news. The use of a Cushite (African) messenger for the pivotal news about the king&rsquo;s son is another instance of the Gentile-as-faithful-witness pattern that runs through 2 Samuel: Ittai the Gittite, Uriah the Hittite, now the Cushite. The outsider carries the news that the insider refused to carry; the Gentile bears the message of the anointed king&rsquo;s victory. This pattern anticipates the Gentile mission of Acts: the nations become the primary bearers of the gospel after its initial rejection at the center (Acts 13:46-47; Rom 11:11). The Cushite running to David is a type of the Gentiles running to the gospel.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ahimaaz presses Joab again for permission to run — &lsquo;whatever may happen, let me also run after the Cushite.&rsquo; Joab&rsquo;s second refusal — &lsquo;why will you run, my son, when you will have no news rewarded?&rsquo; — is overridden by Ahimaaz&rsquo;s persistence. The eager messenger who runs without being commissioned to carry a specific answer typifies the zeal that outruns official authorization, a tension throughout the NT: the disciples who spread the gospel ahead of official commission (Acts 8:4, the scattered believers preaching wherever they went), the enthusiasm of Aquila and Priscilla teaching Apollos (Acts 18:26). Zeal for the king&rsquo;s cause is not wrong; it sometimes needs the wisdom of Joab&rsquo;s caution.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Ahimaaz runs by the way of the plain (the Jordan Valley road) and overtakes the Cushite — his knowledge of terrain gives him a speed advantage. The race between two messengers bearing different aspects of the same news typifies the complexity of the gospel&rsquo;s proclamation: different bearers, different emphases, the same ultimate story. Paul uses the image of running to describe his own proclamation (Gal 2:2; 1 Cor 9:24-26); the courier who knows the terrain is the preacher who knows his context. Ahimaaz arrives first but with an incomplete message — a type of the partial knowledge that characterizes all human proclamation &lsquo;until we see face to face&rsquo; (1 Cor 13:12).</p>",
    "24": "<p>David sits between the two gates — the outer and inner — waiting for news, with the watchman on the roof between. The image of the king waiting at the gate between two gates is a liminal posture: the king occupies the threshold between what is known and what is yet to come. The watchman on the roof who watches for runners is the type of the prophets who watch for the coming of the messenger of salvation (Hab 2:1; Isa 52:7, &lsquo;how beautiful upon the mountains are the feet of him who brings good news&rsquo;). The king at the gate, the watchman on the roof, the runner in the distance — all three are gathered in the typological scene that anticipates the proclamation of Christ&rsquo;s victory.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The watchman calls down — &lsquo;if he is alone, there is news in his mouth&rsquo; — and David says, &lsquo;he is a good man, and comes with good news.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s confident interpretation of a lone runner as a bearer of good news (<em>ṭôḇ ʾîš ûḇĕśôrāh ṭôḇāh bᵉpîhû</em>) reflects his theological conviction that YHWH has acted on his behalf. The <em>bĕśôrāh</em> — good news, gospel — is the OT root of the NT&rsquo;s <em>euangelion</em>. When David declares &lsquo;he comes with good news,&rsquo; he is the type of every hearer who recognizes the runner as a gospel-bearer before the message is spoken. Faith that anticipates the good news before it arrives in full is the pattern of Abraham who &lsquo;saw my day and was glad&rsquo; (John 8:56).</p>",
    "26": "<p>A second runner appears, and the watchman reports to the king — &lsquo;another man running alone.&rsquo; David again declares him a bearer of good news. The king&rsquo;s double declaration of good news before hearing the content encodes a theological posture: the anointed king who trusts YHWH reads all approaching messengers through the lens of YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness. This is the eschatological expectation that shapes biblical prayer and praise — Psalm 121:1 (&lsquo;I lift my eyes to the hills — from where does my help come?&rsquo;), Psalm 130:5-6 (&lsquo;I wait for YHWH, my soul waits, and in his word I hope&rsquo;). Trust in the covenant God precedes specific news; good news is expected because YHWH&rsquo;s character guarantees it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The watchman identifies the first runner&rsquo;s gait as Ahimaaz&rsquo;s — &lsquo;the running of the first is like the running of Ahimaaz son of Zadok.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s response: &lsquo;he is a good man, and comes with good news.&rsquo; The recognition of the runner by his manner of running before he arrives is a type of the NT&rsquo;s claim that Christ is recognized before he speaks — by the breaking of bread (Luke 24:35), by the sound of his voice (John 10:4, the sheep know his voice), by the wounds in his hands (John 20:27). The faithful one is identified by characteristic marks before the formal encounter; the kingdom of God is recognized by those with eyes to see before its full arrival.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ahimaaz&rsquo;s greeting to David — <em>šālôm</em>, &lsquo;peace&rsquo; — is followed by a prostration and an attribution of victory to YHWH: &lsquo;Blessed be YHWH your God, who has delivered up the men who raised their hand against my lord the king.&rsquo; The first word from the victorious battle is <em>šālôm</em> and a doxology — exactly the pattern of resurrection appearances where the risen Christ greets his disciples with &lsquo;peace be with you&rsquo; (John 20:19, 21, 26; Luke 24:36). The announcement of military victory that begins with peace and blessing for YHWH is the prototype of the resurrection announcement that begins with shalom and ends with a commission to proclaim what YHWH has done.</p>",
    "29": "<p>David&rsquo;s first question after hearing the greeting — &lsquo;is it well with the young man Absalom?&rsquo; — reveals that the king&rsquo;s heart has one central concern beneath the battle&rsquo;s outcome. Ahimaaz gives a deliberately incomplete answer: &lsquo;when Joab sent the king&rsquo;s servant and me your servant, I saw a great commotion but did not know what it was.&rsquo; The evasion protects the messenger from delivering news he knows will break the king. The pattern of partial disclosure and protective evasion runs through the resurrection narratives: Mary weeping, the angels&rsquo; questions before the announcement, the disciples&rsquo; gradual recognition. The full news of what has happened arrives in stages, measured to the receiver&rsquo;s capacity to bear it.</p>",
    "30": "<p>David says to Ahimaaz &lsquo;turn aside and stand here&rsquo; — placing the incomplete-messenger to the side while waiting for the Cushite&rsquo;s fuller report. The incomplete messenger who must stand aside while the full truth arrives is a type of the partial revelation of the OT that must stand aside when the fullness of Christ arrives (Heb 1:1-2: &lsquo;in many portions and in many ways, God spoke to our fathers by the prophets, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&rsquo;). The partial messenger is not dismissed but stands to the side — honored, still present, but superseded by the fuller word.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The Cushite arrives and announces: &lsquo;Good news, my lord the king! For YHWH has delivered you today from the hand of all who rose up against you.&rsquo; The Gentile messenger brings the fullest statement of divine vindication — <em>YHWH šᵉpāṭᵉḵā hayyôm miyyaḏ kol haqāmîm ʿālêḵā</em>. The nations bearing the full gospel news — the pattern of Acts&rsquo; movement from Jerusalem through Samaria to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8) — is typified in the Cushite who runs to the king with the good news of deliverance. The Gentile mission is not an afterthought but embedded in the narrative logic of how David&rsquo;s victories are proclaimed.</p>",
    "32": "<p>David repeats his question: &lsquo;is it well with the young man Absalom?&rsquo; The Cushite&rsquo;s reply is the most carefully worded answer in the narrative: &lsquo;may the enemies of my lord the king, and all who rise against you for evil, be like that young man.&rsquo; The Cushite has told the truth without saying the word &lsquo;dead&rsquo; — allowing the king to hear the news in the form of a curse-blessing that preserves the messenger&rsquo;s dignity and the king&rsquo;s grief. The wisdom of the Cushite&rsquo;s phrasing is the wisdom of pastoral sensitivity in proclaiming difficult truth — the truth is not softened or changed, but it is offered in a form the hearer can receive. The gospel similarly announces the death of sin and self in a form that becomes liberation rather than condemnation for those who believe.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>The anger of YHWH was kindled against Israel, and he moved David against them to say, &lsquo;go, number Israel and Judah.&rsquo; The theological problem — YHWH incites David to do what he then punishes — is partially resolved by 1 Chron 21:1 where Satan, not YHWH, is the inciting agent. The two accounts are not in flat contradiction: YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign permissive will allows the adversary&rsquo;s instigation (as in Job 1-2) to accomplish a providential purpose — in this case, the designation of the future temple site through the crisis of plague and atonement. The harder reading (YHWH as direct agent) is typologically more pointed: the cross itself is attributed both to human wickedness and to YHWH&rsquo;s determinate plan (Acts 2:23); divine sovereignty and human culpability operate simultaneously.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David commands Joab to number all the tribes of Israel from Dan to Beersheba — the full Abrahamic extent. The same geographic formula (&lsquo;from Dan to Beersheba&rsquo;) describes the survey of the Promised Land in Josh 19:47 and 1 Sam 3:20; here it marks the scope of the census. The problem with the census is not counting per se (Moses counted the people twice in Numbers) but the motivation: David is taking a military inventory as if the army&rsquo;s size is what secures the kingdom — trusting in numbers rather than in YHWH (Ps 20:7). The NT equivalent is any form of ministry that substitutes institutional strength for dependence on the Spirit (Zech 4:6: &lsquo;not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit, says YHWH of hosts&rsquo;).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s objection — &lsquo;may YHWH your God add to the people a hundred times as many as they are, while the eyes of my lord the king still see it; but why does my lord the king delight in this thing?&rsquo; — is remarkable because it comes from Joab, who has just murdered Absalom against the king&rsquo;s command. The man who violated covenant in ch18 now exercises more theological discernment than the king in ch24. This moral reversal is characteristic of the narrator&rsquo;s realism about human goodness: even flawed characters can voice covenant truth. The NT&rsquo;s preservation of morally complex figures (Peter, who denies Christ and yet preaches Pentecost) reflects the same honest anthropology.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The king&rsquo;s word prevails against Joab and the commanders — the authority of the anointed king overrides even wise counsel to the contrary. The parallel with Solomon asking for wisdom (1 Kings 3) and with Rehoboam rejecting wise counsel (1 Kings 12:8) establishes a pattern: the king&rsquo;s use or misuse of royal authority has covenant consequences that no human advisor can prevent. The typological weight is heavy for ecclesiology: the authority of Christ is absolute, but it is exercised in perfect covenant faithfulness; the misuse of delegated authority (by David, by Rehoboam, by self-aggrandizing leaders) is the persistent OT warning against which Christ&rsquo;s servant-kingship (Mark 10:42-45) stands as the fulfilled correction.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The census journey begins at the Jordan, going to Aroer and the city in the middle of the wadi — Transjordanian territory. The systematic traversal of the nation from east to west, south to north, records the geographic breadth of the Davidic kingdom. The census route traces the same ground that the Mosaic survey covered in Numbers; David is in some sense redoing what Moses did — but without the divinely commanded purpose of Numbers&rsquo; census (military organization for the conquest). A counting without divine mandate, retracing the path of divinely ordered counting, is the precise shape of presumption: the form of obedience without its authorization.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The journey reaches Gilead and the land of Tahtim-hodshi, then Kadesh in the land of the Hittites — the northern fringe of the Davidic empire. The inclusion of Hittite territory in the census sweep indicates that David is counting beyond the twelve tribes, including client peoples — a form of empire-inventory that goes beyond covenant boundaries. The expansion of the covenant people&rsquo;s identity to include Gentile vassals anticipates the NT&rsquo;s eschatological expansion of the people of God to include all nations (Gal 3:28-29); but where the NT expansion is by covenant inclusion through Christ, David&rsquo;s expansion is by military counting — an attempt to quantify what should be trusted to YHWH&rsquo;s promise.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The census reaches the stronghold of Tyre and the cities of the Hivites and the Canaanites, ending in the Negeb of Judah at Beersheba — south to the patriarchal boundary. Beersheba is the place of Abraham&rsquo;s covenant with Abimelech (Gen 21:31) and the place where YHWH appeared to Jacob (Gen 46:1-4). The census that ends at Beersheba closes a geographic ring that encompasses all of the Abrahamic promise-land, as if to take inventory of what YHWH has given. The irony is that the Abrahamic promise was given without condition and can be trusted without counting — the act of counting what God has promised is itself a form of distrust, an attempt to verify by human inventory what divine fidelity has already guaranteed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>At the end of nine months and twenty days, the completed count returns to Jerusalem. The nine-month duration corresponds to a human pregnancy — the time between conception and birth. The census that takes nine months to complete and ends in national catastrophe (v15) is an anti-pregnancy, a gestation that produces death rather than life. The typological contrast is with the nine months of Mary&rsquo;s pregnancy that ends in the birth of the one who gives life rather than taking it. Human attempts to generate security by counting and inventorying what God has promised always gestate in anxiety and conclude in exposure of the original presumption.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The numbers: eight hundred thousand valiant men in Israel, five hundred thousand in Judah. The scale — 1.3 million warriors — represents David at the height of his military power. The census reveals precisely what it was designed to reveal: a massive army. But the census also reveals what it was not designed to reveal: that David&rsquo;s heart had turned from trust in YHWH to reliance on numbers. The NT equivalent is Paul&rsquo;s rejection of &lsquo;worldly wisdom&rsquo; and worldly metrics of success in 1 Cor 1:26-29: God chose what is weak and low to shame the strong and the high, so that no human being might boast before God. A kingdom that depends on its numbers is not yet the kingdom of God.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Before David rises in the morning, YHWH has spoken to Gad the prophet — the divine response arrives before the king can act on the census results. The immediacy of YHWH&rsquo;s response through a prophet who speaks before David has processed the completed census establishes that YHWH&rsquo;s covenant attention is immediate and personal. Gad is David&rsquo;s seer (<em>ḥōzēh</em>) — the king has access to a prophetic voice, a covenant communication channel. The NT&rsquo;s equivalent is the Paraclete who convicts of sin, righteousness, and judgment (John 16:8-11): the Spirit who speaks to the king&rsquo;s heart before the consequences of the sin have fully unfolded, offering the path of repentance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH gives David three options — a theological structure that recurs in OT covenant judgment (the three-choice pattern here parallels the three choices offered to Elijah, and the three-fold testing of Job). The offering of choices rather than a unilateral sentence is an expression of YHWH&rsquo;s covenant relationship with the king: the suzerain disciplines the vassal but includes the vassal in the choice of discipline. This covenantal participation in one&rsquo;s own discipline is a type of the NT&rsquo;s &lsquo;repentance unto life&rsquo; — God does not merely sentence but invites the sinner into the process of restoration. The offering of choices is grace within judgment, not the elimination of judgment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The three options are seven years of famine, three months of fleeing before enemies, or three days of pestilence. The three-three-seven pattern (days-months-years) presents judgment in increasing duration but decreasing immediacy: famine requires years to compound, flight requires months of exhaustion, pestilence is three days of acute divine action. David&rsquo;s choice of the third option (fall into YHWH&rsquo;s hand rather than man&rsquo;s) is the most theologically precise response to covenant discipline: it is better to suffer under the God who is &lsquo;merciful and gracious, slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love&rsquo; (Exod 34:6-7) than under human enemies who have no such covenant obligation to mercy.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David&rsquo;s prayer — <em>ṣar lî meʾōḏ nippəlāh nāʾ bᵉyaḏ YHWH kî rabbîm raḥămāyw ûḇîyaḏ ʾāḏām ʾal ʾeppōlāh</em>, &lsquo;I am in great distress; let us fall into the hand of YHWH, for his mercies are great; but do not let me fall into the hand of man&rsquo; — is the most theologically transparent moment in the Davidic narrative. David chooses YHWH&rsquo;s hand even knowing it means plague, because he trusts YHWH&rsquo;s character over human mercy. The antitype is Gethsemane: &lsquo;not my will but yours be done&rsquo; (Luke 22:42). Both David and Christ submit to the Father&rsquo;s discipline and judgment with trust in his character — David because his mercies are great, Christ as the one who is himself the mercy of God embodied (John 1:14: &lsquo;grace and truth came through Jesus Christ&rsquo;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>YHWH sends a pestilence on Israel from the morning until the appointed time, and seventy thousand of the people die from Dan to Beersheba. The seventy thousand deaths span the exact geographic range of the census (Dan to Beersheba, v2) — the judgment corresponds precisely to the sin&rsquo;s scope. The typological pattern is that the sin of the leader generates corporate consequences: the people bear the cost of the king&rsquo;s pride. This is the Adam-pattern (Gen 3:17-19; Rom 5:12) and its OT recapitulation in every unfaithful king whose sin corrupts the nation. Christ as the Second Adam reverses this pattern: the obedience of one (Rom 5:19) generates life for many, and the corporate consequences of his faithful covenant-keeping are received by all who are in him.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David sees the angel who is striking the people and cries out: &lsquo;behold, I have sinned, and I have done wickedly. But these sheep, what have they done? Please let your hand be against me and against my father&rsquo;s house.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s intercession — <em>ʾānōḵî ḥāṭāʾtî wᵉʾānōḵî hāʿăwêtî ûʾēlleh haṣṣōʾn māh ʿāśû</em> — is the most Christ-shaped moment of the David narrative. The king who confesses his own sin and asks for the punishment to fall on himself rather than on his people models the mediatorial logic of the atonement: the leader takes the judgment the followers deserve. Christ&rsquo;s intercession goes further — he not only asks for the judgment to fall on himself but undergoes it completely (Isa 53:4-6; 2 Cor 5:21), whereas David can only ask; Christ can and does take the full weight.</p>",
    "19": "<p>David goes up to the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite as Gad commanded. The obedience to the prophetic command — going to a specific site designated by divine instruction — is the same pattern as every OT act of worship at a divinely designated place: the tabernacle site in the wilderness, the altar at Bethel, the place YHWH will choose (Deut 12:5). The Jebusite&rsquo;s threshing floor is outside the categories of Israelite sacred space; it is a Gentile agricultural site that YHWH designates for an altar. The inclusiveness of the designation points forward: the temple will be built at this spot, and the temple is the &lsquo;house of prayer for all nations&rsquo; (Isa 56:7; Mark 11:17). The Gentile threshing floor becomes the center of universal worship.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Araunah looks out and sees the king and his servants coming toward him; he goes out and bows before the king with his face to the ground. The Jebusite owner prostrates before the king — a Gentile rendering covenantal honor to the Davidic ruler. The image anticipates the eschatological vision of Ps 72:11 (&lsquo;may all kings fall down before him, all nations serve him&rsquo;) and the NT&rsquo;s proclamation that every knee will bow before the Son of David (Phil 2:10-11). The Gentile Araunah who bows before David and offers his threshing floor for YHWH&rsquo;s altar is the type of the nations who will bring their glory into the heavenly Jerusalem (Rev 21:24-26).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Araunah asks why the king has come and David replies that he has come to buy the threshing floor to build an altar to YHWH, so that the plague may be restrained from the people. The commercial transaction that purchases the atonement-site is explicit: David will pay for the altar rather than receive it as a gift. The site of atonement must be purchased — not taken, not received as charity, but bought at full price. This anticipates the costliness of the true atonement: Christ did not receive life for his people as a transaction-free gift but paid the full price of the covenant curse (Gal 3:13; 1 Pet 1:18-19). The altar site purchased by David foreshadows the price paid for the definitive atonement enacted at the same hill (Moriah, 2 Chron 3:1).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Araunah offers to give the king everything needed — oxen for burnt offerings, threshing sledges and yokes of the oxen for wood, and the wheat for the grain offering. The Jebusite&rsquo;s generosity is the immediate prompting of mercy: he wants the plague on the people to stop and offers everything he has. The willingness of the Gentile owner to give everything for Israel&rsquo;s atonement is a type of the Gentile nations&rsquo; incorporation into the people of God at the eschatological temple: the nations contribute their wealth and resources to the worship of Israel&rsquo;s God (Isa 60:5-7; Hag 2:7). The Gentile who has no stake in Israel&rsquo;s covenant becomes a willing contributor to its restoration.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Araunah&rsquo;s prayer-formula — <em>hakōl nātan ʾarawnāh lammelek wᵉyōʾmer ʾarawnāh ʾel hammelek YHWH ʾĕlōhêḵā yirṣᵉḵā</em>, &lsquo;all this Araunah gives to the king. And Araunah said to the king, YHWH your God accept you&rsquo; — is a Gentile&rsquo;s blessing on Israel&rsquo;s king in YHWH&rsquo;s name. The Jebusite, whose city Jerusalem is, pronounces a blessing using the covenant name that in the previous generation belonged only to Israel. The expansion of YHWH&rsquo;s name onto Gentile lips in a blessing formula anticipates Paul&rsquo;s citation of Hosea in Rom 9:25-26: &lsquo;those who were not my people I will call my people.&rsquo; The Gentile who blesses in YHWH&rsquo;s name at the threshing floor is the OT seed of the universal priesthood that the NT fully realizes.</p>",
    "24": "<p>David refuses Araunah&rsquo;s offer with the famous words: <em>lōʾ ʾeqaḥ mimməḵā wᵉhāʿălōtî laYHWH ʾĕlōhay ʿōlôt ḥinnām wᵉlōʾ ʾazᵉḇeh laYHWH ʾĕlōhay ʿōlôt ʾăšer lōʾ ʾᵉkallêl</em>, &lsquo;I will not offer to YHWH my God burnt offerings that cost me nothing.&rsquo; The theological principle encoded in David&rsquo;s refusal is the most explicit OT articulation of the costliness of true sacrifice: worship that costs nothing is no worship at all. This is the typological counterpart of the cross&rsquo;s absolute costliness — the Son of God gives not a costless gift but his own life, the most valuable thing in the universe, for the atonement of sin. David&rsquo;s fifty shekels of silver for the threshing floor points toward the price &lsquo;not of perishable things such as silver or gold&rsquo; but of &lsquo;the precious blood of Christ&rsquo; (1 Pet 1:18-19).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(c, FILL)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2samuel', c)

    import json as _j
    inter = _j.load(open(ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / '2samuel.json'))
    incomplete = []
    for ch in sorted(inter.keys(), key=int):
        total = len(inter[ch])
        have = len(c.get(str(ch), {}))
        if have < total:
            incomplete.append(f'ch{ch}: {have}/{total}')
    if incomplete:
        print('  Still incomplete:', ', '.join(incomplete))
    else:
        print('  2samuel/christ: all chapters complete')
    total_i = sum(len(v) for v in inter.values())
    total_h = sum(len(v) for v in c.values())
    print(f'  Overall 2samuel/christ: {total_h}/{total_i}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
